Text: France takes the match 3-0 (25-12, 25-14, 28-26).

A controversial call gives Japan a set point at 24-23, but Kevin Tillie shows great composure to keep his side in it, his spike, bringing France to deuce. Ngapeth was key late, giving his side a couple of opportunities, and when his spike put France ahead for their third match point at 27-26, Mory Sidibe closed it out (28-26) with a wonderful block stuff for a score.
Ishikawa subs in to serve at 23-22 for Japan, and fires it into the net. Back to the bench he goes. 23-23.
A service error by Masahiro Yanagida, and then a Shimizu spike goes long -- suddenly Japan's lead has disappeared. It's 22-22, and France hopes the momentum can stay with them.
A high-flying spike by Earvin Ngapeth has France now within one point, 20-19.
Japan edges back ahead four points, as an Asano trickler finds its way past three French blockers. 18-14 for Japan.
A pair of blocks by Tillie and Mory Sidibe has France fired up, and now within two of Japan, 15-13.
Consecutive spikes by Tillie out wide has France back within striking distance at 15-14. Japan calls for time.
An ace by Akihiro Yamauchi puts Japan ahead by six at 12-6, prompting the visiting side to regroup. Time-out for France.

After a wonderful rally, Japan's captain Shimizu fires a hard spike at France's libero Jenia Grebennikov, which flies off his chest and into the crowd. Japan still ahead 5-2, and the hometown crowd is finally showing some energy. They'll need to keep this energy going if Japan is to have any hope today against this tough French squad.

Opening point of the third seems to have given Japan some spark. A wonderful get by Asano leads to a Masahiro Yanagida spike to make it 1-0 Japan. They take two more to make it 3-0, the biggest lead they've held today.

After Japan's captain Shimizu fights off one set point, Kevin Le Roux takes the second set for the visitors with a lovely soft tip at the net that falls among Japan's defenders. Shimazu Arena just exhaled a collective sigh of disappointment. Things do not look good for Japan.

With France ahead 21-12 here in the second, Japan hasn't had much to smile about. Their diminuative opposite Hiroaki Asano (178cm tall) has had some success on the attack in this set, but that's about it.

Tillie and Le Goff both attacking well for France, with five and four points respectively in the set so far. It's 16-9 at the second TTO. Japan's defense isn't quite as impressive as it was in the first leg a week ago versus the Czechs.
Japan manages a couple of scores from Shimizu and Hiroaki Asano, but a Le Goff spike interrupts the momentum. 9-4, France still in full control.
France again pushes ahead early to start the second, going up five on an ace from Kevin Le Roux, 6-1.

Japan really couldn't find any momentum in the first set, with France's blockers not allowing Ishikawa or Shimizu to do much of anything. The set was a breeze for France, taking it 25-12. If Japan hopes to turn it around, they'll need to grab an early lead in the second to light a fire under the hometown crowd.

By jumping ahead of Japan early, France appears to have taken the crowd out of the game in this first set. They aren't making much noise in Kyoto here at all right now. 19-6, France is thoroughly dominating Japan, much to their surprise.

Nicolas Le Goff has been serving well on another run of five unanswered scores for France to reach 15-4. Japan's captain Kunihiro Shimizu finally ends the streak with a spike down the middle, to make it 15-5.
Japan's young star Yuki Ishikawa tries to get his side going, but misfires a spike wide, to fall further behind at 11-4. Time-out Japan.

Both France and Japan showed some nerves to start, exchanging points to reach 3-3. But France has settled down and pulled ahead with five in a row (8-3 at the TTO). Kevin Tillie is serving well, with an ace as part of that run.
Teams just about finished with warm-ups. Kyoto fans are eager for a competitive match today!
Kyoto fans are out in full force to support the home team Japan today against France! Just under an hour to go before match time.
